w = img.shape[1]
strp_w = int(w / 15)
cur_w = 0
strps = []

for i in range(15):
    if i == 14:
        strp = img[:, cur_w:-1]
    else:
        strp = img[:, cur_w:cur_w + strp_w]
        cur_w = cur_w + strp_w
        
    strps.append(strp)

Task 3: Reconstruct the image¶

Now reconstruct the original given a shuffled list of strips.

Solution sketch¶

In order to reconstruct the original image, you'll need to examine the boundary pixels of various patches. Patches whose boundary pixels "match scores" are high are more likely to be neighbouring patches. One way to compute match scores is to treat each boundary as a real-valued vector. Then the problem is simply to compute the similarity between two vectors. I encourage you to use Euclidean distance and Cosine similarity to see if two vectors (i.e., boundaries) are similar.

Mathematically, say $\mathbf{x}_i$ and $\mathbf{x}_j$ are two vectors representing boundaries of two patches. We can compute the similarity between these two vectors as follows.

Euclidean distance¶

$$ \text{Euclidean-distance }(\mathbf{x}_i,\mathbf{x}_j) = \sqrt{\| \mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j \|^2} $$

Cosine similarity¶

$$ \text{Cosine-similarity }(\mathbf{x}_i,\mathbf{x}_j) = \frac{\mathbf{x}_i^T \mathbf{x}_j}{\|\mathbf{x}_i\| \| \mathbf{x}_j\| } $$

Concerns about efficiency¶

I encourage you to think of ways on how to reconstruct the image efficiently.

What to submit¶

You need to submit the following:

  • Your solution and the resulting image;
  • An analysis of which similarity scheme works best for this image; and
  • What techniques did you employ to speed up the process.

import sys

def img_reconstruct(strps, fn, flg):
    d_mat = np.zeros((15, 15)) # rows are right bound distances, col are left bound distances, between boundaries

    for i in range(15):
        for j in range(15):
            if j == i:
                if flg == 0:
                    d_mat[i, j] = 1
                elif flg == 1:
                    d_mat[i, j] = sys.maxsize
            else:
                # flatten the arrays so they are 1 dimensional vectors
                r_b = np.array(strps[i][:, -1]).flatten()
                l_b = np.array(strps[j][:, 0]).flatten()
                # divide the arrays by 255, the maximum RGB value to make sure every value is on a 0-1 scale
                r_b = r_b / 255
                l_b = l_b / 255
                d_mat[i, j] = fn(r_b, l_b)

    org_strps = [strps[0]]
    org_idx = [0]
    r_id = 0
    r_flg = False
    l_flg = False

    while True:
        if len(org_strps) == 15:
            break
        else:
            if r_flg == False:
                min_id = np.argwhere(d_mat[org_idx[r_id]] == np.min(d_mat[org_idx[r_id]]))[0, 0]
                if np.argwhere(d_mat[:, min_id] == np.min(d_mat[:, min_id]))[0, 0] == org_idx[r_id]:
                    org_strps.append(shff_strps[min_id])
                    org_idx.append(min_id)
                    r_id += 1
                else:
                    r_flg = True # hit the right edge
            
            if l_flg == False:
                min_id = np.argwhere(d_mat[:, org_idx[0]] == np.min(d_mat[:, org_idx[0]]))[0, 0]
                if np.argwhere(d_mat[min_id] == np.min(d_mat[min_id]))[0, 0] == org_idx[0]:
                    org_strps.insert(0, shff_strps[min_id])
                    org_idx.insert(0, min_id)
                    r_id += 1
                else:
                    l_flg = True # hit the left edge
    
    for i in range(len(org_idx)):    
        plt.subplot(1, len(org_idx), i+1)
        plt.title(org_idx[i])
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        plt.imshow(org_strps[i])
    plt.show()

    return org_strps

%%time

# Using Cosine similarity

from scipy.spatial.distance import cosine

def fn_cosine(a, b):
    return cosine(a, b)
org_strps = img_reconstruct(shff_strps, fn_cosine, 0)

CPU times: total: 344 ms
Wall time: 346 ms

%%time

# Using Euclidean distance

from numpy.linalg import norm

def fn_norm(a, b):
    return norm(b-a)
org_strps = img_reconstruct(shff_strps, fn_norm, 1)

CPU times: total: 422 ms
Wall time: 426 ms

In [9]:
# Both similarity schemes perfectly reconstructed the original image from the strips.
# Both schemes have the same runtime at 1.63s => there is much different between 2 schemes for the data of this image
# The technique I used is creating an matrix of all of the distances between the strips, 
#  then comparing the minimum values of the columns and rows.
# If the minimum value of both row and column is in the same cell, 
#  the indexes of that cell will be the 2 perfectly matched strips.
# If not => the algorithm hit the right/left edge of the image.
# The algorithm checks both sides in same iteration to minimize runtime.
# Downside: compute the distances matrix can cost a considerable amount of space and runtime.
